Parliament, Sunday 19 February 2023 – The 2023 Budget Speech, a Ministerial briefing on healthcare and a Member’s statement on the state of readiness for the academic year 2023 will take centre stage in the parliamentary programme this week.  Minister of Finance, Mr Enoch Godongwana, is scheduled to deliver the 2023 Budget Speech at a sitting of the National Assembly (NA) to be held at the Cape Town City Hall at 2pm on Wednesday, 22 February.  Minister Godongwana will, as part of the 2023 Budget Speech, also introduce the Appropriation Bill and table the Division of Revenue Bill to Parliament.  President Cyril Ramaphosa, in his State of the Nation Address on 9 February, announced government’s plans to address South Africa’s energy crisis and prevailing socio-economic challenges. In this regard, Minister Godongwana will provide details of spending and revenue collection proposals to implement these plans.He will also outline the funds to be allocated to different spheres of government, departments and entities.  On Tuesday at 10:00, Minister of Health, Dr Joe Phaahla will brief the delegates to the National Council of Provinces (NCOP) on the provision of healthcare services under the theme: “Mitigating the negative impact of load shedding in the provision of healthcare services.” On the same day at 14:00, the National Assembly (NA) will hold a debate on the Agricultural Product Standards Amendment Bill and the National Veld and Forest Fire Amendment Bill.  The Agricultural Product Standards Amendment Bill seeks to amend the Agricultural Product Standards Act, 1990, to provide for auditing of a product for management control systems; to make provision for the setting of tariffs by assignees on a cost-recovery basis and to make further provisions for the Minister to make regulations pertaining to audit and management control systems.  The National Veld and Forest Fire Amendment Bill seeks to amend the National Veld and Forest Fire Act, 1998, so as to provide for the facilitation of the formation of fire protection associations by a municipality or a traditional council; to compel a municipality, state-owned enterprise, public entity or other organ of state which owns land to join the fire protection associations; to extend the powers of entry, search, seizure and arrest to peace officers and traditional leaders and to amend the title of the Act to the National Veldfire Act.  During the NA’s Thursday hybrid plenary sitting, starting at 2pm, Minister of Higher Education, Science and Innovation, Dr Blade Nzimande, will deliver a statement to the House on the post-school education and training sector state of readiness for the academic year 2023 and related matters. The sitting will also consider the report of the Portfolio Committee on Home Affairs on the amendments proposed by the NCOP on the Electoral Amendment Bill.  There are 41 committee meetings, public hearings on Bills and hearings on parliamentary oversight issues scheduled for this week, including:  TUESDAY, 21 FEBRUARY 2023  Portfolio Committee on Mineral Resources and Energy, Update to the Committee on the following referrals: Mining Affected Communities United in Action (MACUA) and Women Affected Communities in Action (WAMUA); Organisation Undoing Tax Abuse (OUTA); Swartkops Sea Salt/SIMAPA; Energy crisis; Information requested and received from the Department of Mineral Resources and Energy  Standing Committee on Finance, Briefing by the Auditor-General on audit outcomes of National Treasury and its entities; Briefing by National Treasury and SARS on their annual reports; Consideration of letter from Independent Commission for the Remuneration of Public Office Bearers: Draft Job Profiles of Commissioners of the FFC  Portfolio Committee on Justice and Correctional Services, Finalization of the Prevention and Combating of Hate Crimes and Hate Speech Bill  Committee for Section 194 Enquiry, Hearing Day 47 – Mr Rodney Mataboge to appear before the Committee  WEDNESDAY, 22 FEBRUARY 2023  Portfolio Committee on Police, Deliberations Third Quarter Crime Statistics (2022/23 FY)  Portfolio Committee on Public Service and Administration, Briefing by the Department of Public Service and Administration, National School of Government and Centre for Public Service Innovation on the first, second and third quarter performance of the 2022/23 financial year; Briefing by the Public Service Commission on the first, second and third quarter performance of the 2022/23 financial year]  Portfolio Committee on Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs, Engagement on the state of Emfuleni Local Municipality by: Emfuleni Local Municipality, Sedibeng District Municipality, Office of the Auditor-General Gauteng, Provincial Treasury and COGTA, SALGA and Department of Cooperative Governance  Portfolio Committee on Trade and Industry, Briefing by the NEF on its first and second quarter financial and non-financial performance for the 2022/23 financial year  Committee for Section 194 Enquiry, Hearing Day 48 – Mr Rodney Mataboge to appear before the Committee  Portfolio Committee on Health, Engagement with the European Parliament’s Special Committee for the Covid-19 pandemic on a possible international treaty on pandemics, the approach to vaccine diplomacy, global solidarity and universal and equitable  THURSDAY, 23 FEBRUARY 2023  Committee for Section 194 Enquiry, Hearings: Day 49 – Mr Rodney Mataboge to appear before the Committee  Joint Meeting: Standing Committee on Finance, Standing Committee on Appropriations, Select Committee on Finance and Select Committee on Appropriations, Briefing by the Minister of Finance on the 2023 Budget  Joint Standing Committee on Defence, Consideration of First Term Programme and 2023 outlook in terms of Annual Performance Plan; Briefing by the DOD on 3-year overview of standing commitments and the annual cost of incurred to fulfil these commitments against the funding provided; Briefing by the DOD on 3-year overview of ordered ad hoc deployments and the annual cost of incurred to fulfil these deployments against the funding provided; Final consideration and adoption of the JSCD mid-term Report; Update on JSCD-PCDMV Study Tour application  FRIDAY, 24 FEBRUARY 2023  Joint Standing Committee on Financial Management of Parliament, Presentation by the Content Advisor/Researcher: Legislative mandate/role of the Committee, and key issues, which require the strategic decisions of the Committee; Content Advisor/ Researcher’s overview of the Committees activities from 2019 to 2022 and the implementation of its recommendations; Consideration and adoption of Committee minutes and reports: 2 December 2022; Report of the JSCFMP on Parliaments revised 2022/23 and draft 2023/23 annual performance plans and budget; Report on the JSCFMP on Parliaments performance in the first half of 2022/23  Portfolio Committee on Transport, Consideration and adoption of reports on the Transport Appeal Tribunal Amendment Bill and the Marine Pollution (Prevention of pollution from Ships) Amendment Bill public hearings; Consideration and adoption of Committee report on Public Protector Report No. 37 of 2018-19; Consideration and adoption of Committee report on the Department of Transport 2022/23 second quarter expenditure  Portfolio Committee on Mineral Resources and Energy, A comprehensive briefing by the Department of Mineral Resources & Energy (DMRE) and the Independent Power Producers Office on the Independent Power Producers Procurement Programme  Portfolio Committee on Sport, Arts and Culture, Briefing by the 2023 Netball World Cup Local Organising Committee (LOC) on the state of readiness in preparation for the Netball World Cup  Portfolio Committee on Water and Sanitation, Presentation by the Department of Water and Sanitation on a cumulative report providing an overview and assessment of the work of water boards as reflected in the 2021/22 Annual Reports of Water Boards; Presentations by Amatola Water, Lepelle Northern Water and Magalies Water Boards: synopsis and overview of their work as reflected in the 2021/22 Annual Reports.  For the latest full schedule of committee meetings (updated regularly), please click:https://www.parliament.gov.za/parliament-programme   ISSUED BY THE PARLIAMENT OF THE REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA Enquiries: Moloto Mothapo Although ordinary citizens may not submit bills to Parliament, they may lobby MPs or committees to introduce legislation that deals with their concerns. African National Congress on the provincial list for the province of Gauteng